\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
In summary, we have introduced DALWGAN, a novel framework that combines adaptive latent space learning with a diffusion-based purification stage to address inherent challenges in generative modeling. By refining latent codes through a controlled diffusion process, our method successfully mitigates mismatches between the learned representations and the true data manifold, thereby enhancing sample quality and stability. The proposed compound loss function, which integrates the Wasserstein GAN loss, a rank penalty, and a diffusion purification loss, ensures that generated outputs faithfully capture the underlying structure of the data. Extensive experiments on both synthetic and real-world datasets validate the effectiveness of the approach, with significant improvements observed in latent structure alignment, visual fidelity, and convergence stability. Future work may explore more complex generator architectures, incorporate stochastic elements, and extend the framework to high-resolution image synthesis. Overall, DALWGAN represents a promising advancement in robust generative modeling.

